### Prototype Chain and `this` — Two Orthogonal Systems

These are completely separate mechanisms that are often conflated in interviews:
- **Prototype chain** — answers "where is this *property* found?" (property lookup)
- **`this`** — answers "what *object* does this function operate on?" (execution context)

```javascript
// --- Prototype chain: property lookup ---
const animal = {
  breathe() { return `${this.name} breathes`; }
};

const dog = Object.create(animal);
dog.name = 'Rex';
dog.bark = function() { return 'Woof!'; };

console.log(dog.bark());    // 'Woof!' — own property
console.log(dog.breathe()); // 'Rex breathes' — found via prototype chain
// When dog.breathe() is called:
//   1. Prototype chain finds 'breathe' on 'animal'
//   2. 'this' is set to 'dog' (implicit binding — dot notation)

// --- 'this' changes independently of prototype ---
const cat = { name: 'Whiskers' };
console.log(dog.breathe.call(cat)); // 'Whiskers breathes'
// Same function from prototype chain, different 'this'

// --- Object.create vs new ---
function Person(name) {
  this.name = name; // set on the new object
}
Person.prototype.greet = function() {
  return `Hi, I'm ${this.name}`;
};

// new: creates object, sets [[Prototype]] to Person.prototype, runs constructor
const alice = new Person('Alice');
console.log(alice.greet()); // 'Hi, I\'m Alice'
console.log(Object.getPrototypeOf(alice) === Person.prototype); // true

// Object.create: creates object, sets [[Prototype]] directly, NO constructor run
const bob = Object.create(Person.prototype);
// bob has no 'name' — constructor was not called!
console.log(bob.greet()); // 'Hi, I\'m undefined'
bob.name = 'Bob';
console.log(bob.greet()); // 'Hi, I\'m Bob'

// --- Class syntax (ES6) is just cleaner syntax for the same mechanism ---
class Vehicle {
  constructor(type) { this.type = type; }
  describe() { return `A ${this.type}`; }
}
class Car extends Vehicle {
  constructor() { super('car'); }
}
const car = new Car();
console.log(car.describe()); // 'A car' — found via prototype chain
```

**Common interview trap:** `prototype` is a property on **function objects** pointing to the object that will become the `[[Prototype]]` of instances. `__proto__` (or `Object.getPrototypeOf()`) is the actual `[[Prototype]]` link on an instance. `Function.prototype !== Function.__proto__` — even though both exist. When you do `new Foo()`, the instance's `[[Prototype]]` is set to `Foo.prototype`, NOT to `Foo`.

