### Array Methods — map, filter, reduce and the Full Toolkit

**map** — transform each element, always returns same-length array
**filter** — keep elements matching a predicate, may return shorter array
**reduce** — fold array into single value (number, object, array, anything)

```javascript
const orders = [
  { id: 1, user: 'Alice', amount: 120, status: 'shipped' },
  { id: 2, user: 'Bob',   amount: 50,  status: 'pending' },
  { id: 3, user: 'Alice', amount: 200, status: 'shipped' },
  { id: 4, user: 'Carol', amount: 80,  status: 'cancelled' },
  { id: 5, user: 'Bob',   amount: 300, status: 'shipped' },
];

// Pipeline: shipped orders → amounts → total
const totalShipped = orders
  .filter(o => o.status === 'shipped') // [120, 200, 300 orders]
  .map(o => o.amount)                  // [120, 200, 300]
  .reduce((sum, amt) => sum + amt, 0); // 620

console.log(totalShipped); // 620

// reduce to build an index (object from array)
const orderById = orders.reduce((acc, order) => {
  acc[order.id] = order;
  return acc;
}, {});
console.log(orderById[3].user); // 'Alice'

// reduce to group by user
const byUser = orders.reduce((acc, order) => {
  if (!acc[order.user]) acc[order.user] = [];
  acc[order.user].push(order);
  return acc;
}, {});
console.log(byUser.Alice.length); // 2

// Other essential array methods:
// find: first match (or undefined)
const bigOrder = orders.find(o => o.amount > 150);
console.log(bigOrder?.id); // 3

// findIndex: index of first match (or -1)
console.log(orders.findIndex(o => o.user === 'Carol')); // 3

// every / some: boolean tests
console.log(orders.every(o => o.amount > 0));   // true
console.log(orders.some(o => o.status === 'cancelled')); // true

// flat / flatMap: work with nested arrays
const tags = [['js', 'es6'], ['async', 'promises'], ['js', 'closures']];
const allTags = tags.flat(); // ['js', 'es6', 'async', 'promises', 'js', 'closures']
const uniqueTags = [...new Set(allTags)]; // ['js', 'es6', 'async', 'promises', 'closures']

// flatMap: map + flat in one pass (more efficient)
const words = ['hello world', 'foo bar'].flatMap(s => s.split(' '));
console.log(words); // ['hello', 'world', 'foo', 'bar']
```

**Common interview trap:** Chaining `.filter().map()` creates two intermediate arrays. If performance matters on large arrays, merge into one `reduce` pass. Also, `reduce` without an initial value (`[]` second argument) crashes on empty arrays — always provide it.

