### Prototype Chain — hasOwnProperty, for...in, and Class Inheritance

Understanding prototype lookup explains why certain patterns behave unexpectedly.

```javascript
// --- Property lookup order ---
const grandparent = { gp: 'grandparent prop' };
const parent = Object.create(grandparent);
parent.p = 'parent prop';
const child = Object.create(parent);
child.c = 'child prop';

// Lookup walks up the chain:
console.log(child.c);    // 'child prop' — own property
console.log(child.p);    // 'parent prop' — from parent
console.log(child.gp);   // 'grandparent prop' — from grandparent
console.log(child.missing); // undefined — not found in chain

// Check if property is own vs inherited
console.log(child.hasOwnProperty('c'));   // true
console.log(child.hasOwnProperty('p'));   // false — inherited
console.log('p' in child);                // true — includes inherited

// --- for...in iterates inherited properties too ---
for (const key in child) {
  console.log(key); // c, p, gp — ALL enumerable properties up the chain
}

// Filter to own properties only:
for (const key in child) {
  if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(child, key)) {
    console.log(key); // only: c
  }
}
// Modern alternative:
console.log(Object.keys(child));         // ['c'] — own enumerable
console.log(Object.getOwnPropertyNames(child)); // ['c'] — own, including non-enumerable

// --- Class syntax and prototype chain ---
class Animal {
  constructor(name) { this.name = name; } // goes on instance
  speak() { return `${this.name} makes a sound`; } // goes on Animal.prototype
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  speak() { // overrides Animal.prototype.speak
    return `${this.name} barks`;
  }
  describe() {
    return super.speak() + ' (and barks)'; // explicit prototype chain traversal
  }
}

const d = new Dog('Rex');
console.log(d.speak());    // 'Rex barks' — Dog.prototype.speak
console.log(d.describe()); // 'Rex makes a sound (and barks)' — super calls Animal

// Prototype chain of d:
// d -> Dog.prototype -> Animal.prototype -> Object.prototype -> null
console.log(d instanceof Dog);    // true
console.log(d instanceof Animal); // true — walks up chain
```

**Common interview trap:** `for...in` iterates **all** enumerable properties including inherited ones. In older code this caused bugs when methods were accidentally iterable. Modern class methods are non-enumerable by default (they go on the prototype with `enumerable: false`), which is why `for...in` on class instances doesn't expose methods. But plain object methods defined in literals ARE enumerable.

