### Symbols and Well-Known Symbols

Symbols create unique, non-enumerable property keys. Well-known symbols define protocols: Symbol.iterator enables the iterable protocol, Symbol.toStringTag customizes Object.prototype.toString(), and Symbol.hasInstance controls instanceof behavior.

```typescript
const iterable = {
  [Symbol.iterator]() {
    let i = 0;
    return {
      next: () => ({
        value: i++,
        done: i > 3
      })
    };
  },
  [Symbol.toStringTag]: 'CustomIterable'
};

for (const val of iterable) console.log(val); // 0, 1, 2
console.log(Object.prototype.toString.call(iterable)); // [object CustomIterable]
```

**Common interview trap:** Thinking Symbols prevent property access instead of making them non-enumerable.

