### WeakMap for DOM Node Metadata — Leak-Safe Event Registry

A common source of memory leaks in browser apps: storing data keyed by DOM nodes in a regular Map or on the node itself.

```javascript
// PROBLEM: regular Map holds strong references — DOM nodes can't be GC'd
const badRegistry = new Map();
function trackElement(el) {
  badRegistry.set(el, { listeners: [], clicks: 0 });
  // Even after el is removed from DOM and all other refs drop,
  // badRegistry keeps it alive → memory leak
}

// SOLUTION: WeakMap — DOM nodes can be GC'd when removed
const elementData = new WeakMap();

function initElement(el) {
  elementData.set(el, {
    listeners: [],
    cleanupFns: [],
    metadata: { createdAt: Date.now() }
  });
}

function addManagedListener(el, event, handler, options) {
  if (!elementData.has(el)) initElement(el);
  const data = elementData.get(el);

  el.addEventListener(event, handler, options);
  // Store the exact reference so we can remove it
  data.listeners.push({ event, handler, options });
  data.cleanupFns.push(() => el.removeEventListener(event, handler, options));
}

function destroyElement(el) {
  const data = elementData.get(el);
  if (!data) return;
  // Remove all listeners before detaching from DOM
  data.cleanupFns.forEach(fn => fn());
  // Don't need to delete from WeakMap — GC handles it
  el.remove();
}

// Usage
const button = document.createElement('button');
addManagedListener(button, 'click', () => console.log('clicked'));
addManagedListener(button, 'mouseenter', () => console.log('hover'));

destroyElement(button);
// After button is no longer referenced elsewhere,
// WeakMap entry is GC'd — no memory leak

// WeakSet: track which elements have been initialized (without leaking)
const initialized = new WeakSet();

function maybeInit(el) {
  if (initialized.has(el)) return; // already done
  initialized.add(el);
  // setup...
}
// When el is removed and GC'd, WeakSet entry disappears automatically
```

**Common interview trap:** `WeakMap` and `WeakSet` have no `.size` property and are not iterable — this is **intentional**. If you could enumerate them, the GC would need to keep all referenced objects alive to produce a consistent iteration. The non-iterability is what enables the weak reference semantics. If you need to track how many entries you have, use a separate counter that you manually increment/decrement.

